Cute little Japanese cafe, great for brunch. Definitely get their toast and a cup of coffee or tea to go with it!
The bento box was perfection.  I could eat this every week.
Yummy

Absolute favorite cafe in the city! It’s a small place with a few seats inside and one table for outdoor seating. You can get standard drinks like coffee and latte, or the specials like matcha latte and black sesame latte. The matcha latte is one of the best I’ve ever had. Also really enjoyed the ice coffee with the coffee jelly! Don’t let the simplicity of the toasts deceive you. I wasn’t sure if the ham and egg was interesting enough to try, but I was blown away by how good it was. The flavors range from sweet to savory. I recommend in trying all of them. Each is delicious in its own way. They also offer entrees like curry bowls, salads and udon.
Can’t say enough good things about this place. A picture is worth a thousand words though 😉One of my favorite nyc spots! IG- newyorkcitymunchies for more 📸
Cute place, store is very small, but food are great!
This is one of my favorite Japanese restaurants in New York! It’s a super cute space and I love their brunch and dinner options. Their service is always great. Highly recommend!

Very unique, cute cafe with terrific food and hot drinks. I really enjoyed the katsu curry--very flavorful and had much more texture than your typical boxed Japanese curry. Toast was a lot of fun too, the slices of milk bread were huge! Would highly recommend for a brunch or snack to-go.

Davelle is a dream. The homemade toasts are like a cloud with delicious fresh toppings and the curry is hands-down the best I’ve ever had. Pair with a specialty drink or fresh brewed tea to make your soul feel all the feels. Go here, and tip well!

Very expensive. The curry with chicken was good, but nothing special. Ditto for the pour over coffee. It took 20 minutes to get the food and cost $28 (with tip). The runny egg I added to the dish was cold. I won’t return for another curry but perhaps the toasts are a better deal. The interior is adorable and reminded me of some places I’d visited in Japan.

First off, it's such a comforting departure from the prototypical loud, busy NYC restaurant. Patrons seem interested in tasting as they talk in relatively hushed tones in an intimate space. Service is also polite and informative. The food is savory Japanese fusion. Nice spices and texture. Thin shell shrimp, Yuzu edamame, and fried chicken are great appetizers. Entrees that popped include Curry with fried chicken, spicy cod caviar spaghetti, and Uni tomato spaghetti. The Ginjos, including the one from Brooklyn, are outstanding.

Don’t really get the hype around this place. It’s super tiny, so getting a table is almost impossible. I got their famous berry cream toast to go, and it took them forever to prepare it. It honestly is just overpriced ($9!) toast, that yes, is very instagrammable, but not much else to it.
Great ambience, and staff. Oden was great, if you want something light.
Overpriced for what you get. The curry was good but the omurice was dry and tasteless.
Nice place, cozy and comfortable. Food and service was good!
This place is a gem. Great vibes and amazing food.

Cozy little Japanese restaurant in LES. Spicy cod roe pasta, mentaiko pasta, was great. Toasts were good, but not surprising. Food portions are kinda small; we ordered two main dishes and two toasts for two of us.
Very great food and nice service.
So good. Delicate flavors and creative dishes. Chicken katsu curry was wonderful as were the unigiri balls. The desert parfait is worth saving room for.
A nice spot for simple, hearty Japanese fusion in the middle of NYC with friendly staff - really like their take on toast. Recommend the mentaiko pasta and Kyoto cold brew.
Everything here was sooooo delicious! Would highly recommend family style so you can try a little bit of everything!

Such a cute little place in LES. Everyone who works there is super chill and friendly. Even though the place is small it’s really warm and comfortable in there.  The tobiko spaghetti was the best I’ve ever had. The food overall was delicious. The oden was dope. Good sake too but it’s pricey so ask how much first lol

Stopped in for a midweek lunch at this cozy all day cafe. Someone clacking away at their laptop in the window, another man dining alone, a few people coming in and out for coffee or lunch to go.  Had some chicken katsu don which was fresh and delicious, a perfect little lunch. My friend and I had coffees which were great, and the one employee taking orders was friendly, genuine, and warm.
Great coffee! Must try toasts. (Might be running out of toasts when going in late.) Also they have very limited seating. Highly recommended if you go on off-peak hours
Delicious food and great staff. The cod roe spaghetti is addictive

Was lured in by the photogenic toasts I saw on Instagram. A friend and I shared the berry & cream cheese and the red bean toasts. The berry & cream cheese one was good, but it wasn't too exciting, and I felt like I could make my own version at home pretty easily. The red bean toast was SO GOOD though.

Food here was so good! Japanese comfort food- chicken katsu curry, shishito peppers, unigiri, uni spaghetti (so good!), and more. The weakest was the ice cream in the affogato which was mealy. The counter seats were a little uncomfortable but overall decor was homey and the waitstaff was super friendly. I would want to come back to try their toasts but maybe at a table instead...
Hospitality is 100%
Fantastic cold brew and latte
This Japanese cafe's food and drink is delicious!
Great food, quiet and intimate. Not pretentious

Super cute store!! The toasts were delicious! Especially the blueberry cream cheese! Strongly recommended:) Came here in the afternoon to get the pic of sun shining through window! See below:) love it

Atmosphere: Welcoming and home-like. Intimate. Great spot for a date!  Space: Small but clean. It's nice not to have serious crowds around  Staff: Extremely attentive. Friendly. Pays attention to details.  Cocktails: ABSOLUTELY DELICIOUS  Price: $$  Overall: The space is small so I wouldn't recommend for large crowds but it's great for a small intimate setting. The staff takes pride into the food and drinks they create and it shows. If your looking for a nice calm night after work, or a break from a Friday, this is the spot. Prices are decent as well. I definitely recommend this spot

(4.5) Great little joint that serves some Japanese-Italian dishes. Got the unigiri & spicy cod caviar spaghetti. I enjoyed both dishes, but I felt the unigiri didn't have enough uni in it.  The pasta had a high price tag for the portion but overall it was a good plate of pasta. A hidden gem tucked away in the LES, would come back to try other items.
Authentic place

Rustic and great atmosphere. Calm jazz music in the background. Authentic food. Epic handdrawn menu.
Epic food and drinks. Matcha Yuzu is epic. I love it so matcha. Barista has super epic hat and coffee skills. Epic.
Beautiful and authentic Japanese drinks. Interesting flavours and chilled atmosphere.

A dainty place with some Kyoto inspired dishes. Ordered the spicy roe pasta and the berry cream cheese toast, both are great. It's a good cafe with a nice ambiance and  Japanese dishes. You wouldn't be disappointed

Good, but overpriced for what it was, especially considering the portions.
Tiny place with tight menu - the roe spaghetti was great!
The food tastes as good as it looks! Perfect quaint little spot. Would recommend trying one toast and one savory dish! The matcha is amazing would highly recommend.
Quaint little place with fine, light, hearty toasts. Really recommend the curry bread and the matcha avocado tofu smoothie. Only downside is that for the portion it's a little on the expensive side.
Tasty curry;)

This hidden gem in the lower east side is a charming little Japanese cafe. It probably sits about 10-15 people comfortably. I came here with two friend and we luckily got a seat at the gold countertop. I ordered the black sesame latte, chicken katsu curry, and the berry and cream cheese toast. Yes, it was a decent amount of food for one person but I was hungry!  The black sesame was surprisingly packed with that nutty black sesame flavor and was delicious iced. Fun fact: They made it in a magic bullet!  The chicken in the chicken katsu curry perfectly crispy and he curry tasted like the typical Japanese curry. The only downside is that the portion was pretty small for $20.  My friend ordered the spicy cod caviar pasta  and I tried and bite and it was SO GOOD. I’ll probably order it next time.  Last but not least, I ordered the berry and cream cheese toast. And to be honest, I ordered it because it was pretty :)
Overpriced hippy cafe with Sun-rise mart quality deli food.
The wait is frustratingly long because they staff will perfect your order, but this place just exudes such a happy, competent tokyo vibe. Both drinks and snacks are delicious.
Really cute ambience. Service was ok - they didn’t have enough hangers or space for my winter coat which was weird given the size of the place... food was ok, maybe brunch is better!

This Japanese cafe is perfect for lowkey meetups with friends, day or night. I’m partial to breakfast with their fabulous coffee, toasts, and omurice—but dinner was tasty too. Another plus: the very knowledgeable bartender helped me figure out what sake would go best with my Japanese curry, and explained all about how the restaurant picks its sake brands. So interesting! It’s a *little* on the pricier side, but still well worth a visit.
Perfect. A place to enjoy coffee at it's finest
Really well-done Japanese comfort food. Every dish (Uni rice ball, katsu curry, chicken cutlets) was a great version of that dish. Great sake list.
Food is delicious. A bit pricey for what you get and for how simple most of the food is but it's nyc.

This hole is to be avoided at all cost: we ordered a dish as the menu said it had octobus balls in it. The dish arrives without it.. when we ask for it they said sorry but they were out of it... shouldn’t any honest place inform you beforehand that they’re out of it - it was why we ordered it. The octopus was replaced by a tiny mushroom slice.. and we charged the full price of course. Just one of the many dishonest details

Amazing experience at Davelle! The mentaiko toast was perfectly savory and the buttered toast balanced the saltiness of the mentaiko. The uni pasta was also delicious; decent portion of uni and the noodles were nice, soft and chewy like instant ramen noodles texture. The chicken katsu with egg was also cooked very nicely. I also got a matcha latte, one of the better oat matcha lattes I’ve had in the city for sure!

Really love this Japanese comfort food restaurant/cafe/sake bar. You cannot go wrong with the spicy cod roe spaghetti. Truly delicious meals to be had here if you're looking for a lovely restaurant in the LES.
Amazing small little place in the LES serving up some amazing Japanese dishes.
Such a cozy cute place, beautiful ambience. The bathroom was so nice. (Weird comment but it is). Eco friendly serving ware. Black sesame latte was so good. Definitely would come back.
Fantastic restaurant! I went for dinner with a friend. We had really good drinks and several dishes. Everything was delicious. I definitely want to go back.
Intimate spot with great food and great coffee.

(Translated by Google) The number of seats is small, but the atmosphere is very good as it is small. The cute interior draws your eye. Mentaiko spaghetti and cafe menus such as Napolitan are fun.  (Original) 席数は少ないですが、こじんまりとしてとても雰囲気がいいです。 可愛いインテリアが目を引きます。 明太子スパゲティや、ナポリタンなど喫茶店メニューが楽しいです。

Davelle is a delightful all day no tipping Japanese cafe that offers tea, coffee, breakfast toasts, oden, as well as lunch and dinner. The menu, at least the choice of entrees is small but I find that this ends up working well. We had the karagee and the pork curry, both were good but the curry was especially flavorful. Both dishes came with a pint sized soup and salad.  The place itself is stylishly decorated, has lots of light making it warm and cozy and very much feels like an oasis.
Cute spot, very friendly.  Curry hits the spot.
Cute little Japanese cafe! The drinks are great, and the food is delicious. Menu is pretty limited though. Not much seating either, but the ambiance of the space is intimate and neat.
Nice and cozy with Japanese European style interior decor. Lovely
incredible little place with the right vibe and excellent, homecooked-but-thoughtful food. owner is super super nice.

I love this place. Great atmosphere, the perfect quiet spot to read a book on a lazy afternoon. Small, rustic, but seemingly lively. AND a really interesting menu, both for breakfast items and otherwise. Everything I’ve tried has been great. AND some of the smoothest, least acidic cold brew i have had in all of LES / East Village. I’m not writing a screenplay, but if i was, i would do it at Davelle.  It’s now occurred to me how hipster this review has become. Just trust me: you’ll like it here.
Small spot that we probably enjoyed the most on our trip. Great little lunch. Wish we had gone back for dinner.

Even if this place is no tipping, I still left a tip because the service, atmosphere and food were all incredibly delightful. I ordered the Sugar Butter toast and a plain pour over coffee for breakfast this morning. I was pleasantly surprised, and honestly almost moved to tears due to how delicious the meal was! I am not kidding! I felt my eyes well up. The fluffy milk bread was perfectly toasted and had a light and sweet coating of sugar, providing a crispy crunch with each bite. The potato salad was out of this world. Seriously underrated. Hands down-probably the best potato salad I have ever tried. The coffee was not too hot and not too cold, it was served to me at the perfect temperature which I appreciated. Sometimes you go to places and they serve you piping hot coffee and you have to wait at least 15 minutes before you can take a sip without burning yourself. The server was so very kind and accommodating. I don't know his name but he was wearing a green beanie and a grey sweatshirt, he was an absolute sweetie. The place itself is quaint but so relaxing. I got there first thing in the morning so it was empty. They played classical music as I enjoyed my breakfast which was perfect background music for this delightful experience. As I left I was thanked by another worker who was a woman and both her and the male server said a kind goodbye to me as I left with my belly full of this delicious food.  I have literally never felt more compelled to get online and write a good review in my life. This was truly a wonderful time I had at Davelle and I will be sure to return on my next trip to New York. Perfect start to my day. If I could rate it 100 stars I would!

Delihtful cafe and delicious Oden style food (slimey things, mostly steamed), as well as great spaggetti and rice with curry. Beautiful and peaceful atmosphere in tiny venue, small menu, and thoughtful kind service.
Fantastic Japanese style curry and all of the oden! BYOB so grab some Sapporo nearby before sitting down for a leisurely meal.
Really delicious food (especially the oden, unigiri, and pasta), cozy atmosphere, great owner that puts a smile on your face. What else could you ask for?

Amazing chicken karaage. It's seriously, quite possibly the best I've had to date. I haven't tried the other dishes but I'm sure they're fantastic as well.  They also has a good selection of coffee drinks.  That being said I still have to ding one star because for the price, I feel I was a little shorted on the amount of chicken I got. I only got 5 fairly small pieces, by the time I finished the chicken I still had plenty of rice left over; definetly feel they could have added a couple more pieces.  Overall though I did enjoy my experience and though I can't afford to go too often, I will definetly be back.
Nice and cozy. Menu is limited but it's good food and reasonable priced. Only had the breakfast but will return for the oden dinner.
Very good Japanese food. The owner Yudai Kanayama is unbelievably talented.
